Miss Collier, our work
is a profession.

242
00:34:50,340 --> 00:34:55,553
A doctor, for example,
doesn't begin to operate...
You're not a doctor.

243
00:34:55,637 --> 00:34:59,974
I read your article
about police brutality in Stapleton.

244
00:35:00,058 --> 00:35:03,019
And the next time "The Staten Island"
"Panorama" decides to investigate...

245
00:35:03,061 --> 00:35:07,023
our methods, I hope
they send a real reporter.
I'm going up there.

246
00:35:10,026 --> 00:35:13,238
And you're certainly not a cop.
And you're not either...

247
00:35:13,321 --> 00:35:15,323
if you don't do
something about this.

248
00:35:15,407 --> 00:35:17,742
Unless, of course, you'd rather
go beat up a few students.

249
00:35:17,826 --> 00:35:19,744
Ever hear of a search warrant,
Miss Civil Liberties?

250
00:35:19,828 --> 00:35:21,788
Well, you haven't got one,
and neither do I.

251
00:35:21,871 --> 00:35:24,791
You mean you're actually gonna stand
here and ask me idiotic questions...

252
00:35:24,874 --> 00:35:28,545
like some dumb courtroom
drama while a man dies?

253
00:35:28,628 --> 00:35:30,922
I saw it.
Saw it happen.

254
00:35:31,006 --> 00:35:34,467
Actually saw it happen.
Calm down, calm down.

255
00:35:34,551 --> 00:35:36,761
Now, you just go back
to your apartment and relax.

256
00:35:36,845 --> 00:35:38,763
And watch you walk off?

257
00:35:38,847 --> 00:35:40,765
You'd like that,
wouldn't you?

258
00:35:40,849 --> 00:35:43,268
That'd make a great story
for your next issue.

259
00:35:43,351 --> 00:35:47,397
"Police refuse to investigate
brutal race murder."

260
00:35:47,480 --> 00:35:49,399
Not a chance, lady.
You stick with us.

261
00:35:49,482 --> 00:35:51,401
And keep
your mouth shut.

262
00:35:51,484 --> 00:35:54,362
I'll do what
I consider necessary.

263
00:36:04,039 --> 00:36:05,957
This isn't
a police state yet.

264
00:36:23,475 --> 00:36:25,435
3-R is this way.

265
00:36:43,703 --> 00:36:45,622
Yes?
Police officer.

266
00:36:45,705 --> 00:36:48,041
Oh, yes? Can I help you?
Are you the lady of the house?

267
00:36:48,124 --> 00:36:50,377
Yes, I am.
You live here alone?

268
00:36:50,460 --> 00:36:52,921
Yes.
Had any company this morning?

269
00:36:52,962 --> 00:36:55,465
Oh, no.
Two people...
That will do, Miss Collier.

270
00:36:55,548 --> 00:36:58,968
If there is some information that
you need, I will be glad to help you,

271
00:36:59,052 --> 00:37:02,013
but as you can see,
I am in the middle of dressing,

272
00:37:02,097 --> 00:37:05,517
so, uh, if you excuse me,
I'll finish.

273
00:37:05,600 --> 00:37:07,519
She's afraid.
You mind...

274
00:37:07,602 --> 00:37:09,813
You mind if we come in?
Just what do you want?

275
00:37:09,896 --> 00:37:12,065
If you don't mind our coming in,
this lady will explain.

276
00:37:12,148 --> 00:37:16,027
Have you the search, um... the search
permission? Have you that?

277
00:37:16,111 --> 00:37:19,698
You mean a search warrant?
Yes, the search warrant.
Have you that?

278
00:37:19,781 --> 00:37:21,950
No.
She's stalling. She's hiding the body.

279
00:37:21,992 --> 00:37:25,120
If you have not the search warrant,
it's not very important.

280
00:37:25,203 --> 00:37:29,082
So if you will excuse me,
I finish to dress.

281
00:37:29,165 --> 00:37:31,543
It'll take me just ten minutes
to get a search warrant,

282
00:37:31,626 --> 00:37:34,546
and while Spinetti here is going
to the trouble of doing that,

283
00:37:34,629 --> 00:37:37,465
I shall naturally have to...
Excuse me.

284
00:37:37,507 --> 00:37:39,592
I don't mean to offend you.
Come in.

285
00:37:39,676 --> 00:37:43,388
But you know, I see all the time
on the television show...

286
00:37:43,471 --> 00:37:46,641
the scene of the evil criminal
and the policeman,

287
00:37:46,725 --> 00:37:48,685
and the policeman
knock on the door...

288
00:37:48,727 --> 00:37:51,646
and the criminal,
he ask about, you know,

289
00:37:51,688 --> 00:37:53,356
what you have ask me...
the search warrant.

290
00:37:53,440 --> 00:37:56,276
But you have not
said to me,

291
00:37:56,359 --> 00:37:58,987
"Open in the name of the law."
You have not said that.

292
00:37:59,029 --> 00:38:03,908
Now, then, Miss...
Danielle. Danielle Breton.

293
00:38:03,992 --> 00:38:06,703
I'm Detective Kelly.
This is Detective Spinetti,

294
00:38:06,786 --> 00:38:09,122
How do you do?
This is Miss Collier, your neighbor...

295
00:38:09,205 --> 00:38:11,708
"from across the way."
Hello. How are you?

296
00:38:11,791 --> 00:38:16,421
Hello.
"Something very unusual"
occurred this morning.

297
00:38:16,504 --> 00:38:19,341
Seems that Miss Collier happened to
glance out of her window...

298
00:38:19,382 --> 00:38:23,553
and saw something which so shocked
and disturbed her...

299
00:38:23,636 --> 00:38:26,639
that she called the police department.
I saw a murder.

300
00:38:29,059 --> 00:38:31,895
Thank you, Miss Collier.

301
00:38:31,978 --> 00:38:34,606
Now, then, Miss Breton,
I suppose you can see...

302
00:38:34,689 --> 00:38:39,152
Miss Collier's apartment from here.
I really don't know.

303
00:38:39,235 --> 00:38:41,821
You know very well
you can.

304
00:38:41,905 --> 00:38:44,199
Yes, there's my window.
This is definitely the right apartment.

305
00:38:44,240 --> 00:38:48,703
Miss Collier, do you spend a lot of time
watching my apartment?

306
00:38:48,745 --> 00:38:51,081
You saw me.
You know you did.

307
00:38:51,164 --> 00:38:53,625
Lf, uh, I have seen you,

308
00:38:53,708 --> 00:38:56,002
then I would have pulled
the shade and if I do that,

309
00:38:56,086 --> 00:38:58,004
I have to give up
all my life...

310
00:38:58,088 --> 00:39:00,674
"to have the privacy."
She did draw the shade.

311
00:39:00,757 --> 00:39:03,677
Obviously once she'd
hidden the body she felt safe.

312
00:39:03,760 --> 00:39:06,096
But it must be here
somewhere.

313
00:39:06,179 --> 00:39:09,349
I can't believe
that this is serious.

314
00:39:09,432 --> 00:39:11,851
He wrote "help"
on this window in his own blood.

315
00:39:11,935 --> 00:39:13,853
And I watched him
write it.

316
00:39:13,937 --> 00:39:16,606
Here he write that?
"Naturally she washed it off."

317
00:39:16,690 --> 00:39:18,983
It's all so obvious.
This girl is protecting someone.

318
00:39:20,819 --> 00:39:24,280
But the murderess
is someone this girl knows.

319
00:39:24,322 --> 00:39:27,826
She was shorter
and had a twisted face...

320
00:39:27,909 --> 00:39:32,539
and stringy hair and was having
a terrible fit of some kind.

321
00:39:32,622 --> 00:39:37,794
You know someone who would fit
that description, Miss Breton?
No.

322
00:39:37,877 --> 00:39:41,089
Good God! I saw the knife!
I saw her stab him!

323
00:39:41,131 --> 00:39:43,800
Could somebody have gotten in here
without your knowledge?

324
00:39:43,883 --> 00:39:47,554
It would be impossible.
I was here all morning.

325
00:39:47,637 --> 00:39:49,597
What about the man
that stayed over?

326
00:39:49,639 --> 00:39:53,393
I was quite alone.

327
00:39:53,476 --> 00:39:57,272
You see, I'm-I'm divorced
from my husband, and still, uh...

328
00:39:57,355 --> 00:40:00,025
Well, it's
very personal, you know.

329
00:40:00,108 --> 00:40:04,320
But Miss Collier, many time at night
I watch the television show...

330
00:40:04,404 --> 00:40:09,075
and I watch the horror film,
and it make me full of fear,

331
00:40:09,159 --> 00:40:11,077
and-and I jump
at every noise.

332
00:40:11,161 --> 00:40:15,206
I understand that when you live alone
it make you... It's very difficult.

333
00:40:15,290 --> 00:40:17,208
I understand that.

334
00:40:21,338 --> 00:40:24,758
What I saw happen
was real.

335
00:40:29,012 --> 00:40:31,598
Mind if we have
a look around?

336
00:40:31,681 --> 00:40:34,059
No, it's perfectly
all right.

337
00:40:35,143 --> 00:40:37,062
Thank you, Miss Collier.

338
00:40:37,145 --> 00:40:39,981
I know you're doing your best
to help the forces of justice,

339
00:40:40,023 --> 00:40:43,318
but they will be better served
by your sitting down.

340
00:40:43,401 --> 00:40:46,654
That body is
here somewhere,

341
00:40:46,696 --> 00:40:48,823
and she knows it.

342
00:40:48,865 --> 00:40:50,825
 How many rooms do you
have, Miss Breton?

343
00:40:50,867 --> 00:40:53,328
Well, uh, there is
the living room here,

344
00:40:53,370 --> 00:40:55,330
and then the bathroom
and the kitchen

345
00:40:55,372 --> 00:40:57,332
and then past
is the bedroom.

346
00:40:57,374 --> 00:40:59,334
You mind if we see
the bathroom?

347
00:40:59,376 --> 00:41:01,836
No. The bathroom
is here.

348
00:41:06,800 --> 00:41:10,428
See? This. And, uh...
Bedroom?

349
00:41:10,512 --> 00:41:12,972
Yes, the bedroom
is down here.

350
00:41:13,056 --> 00:41:16,893
In here.
Coming, Miss Collier?

351
00:41:16,976 --> 00:41:20,438
Oh, uh, 'scuse me
for a second.

352
00:42:10,864 --> 00:42:14,743
 Miss Collier,
would you stick with us, please?

353
00:42:28,757 --> 00:42:30,925
I understand.
Have you looked under the bed?

354
00:42:30,967 --> 00:42:32,927
I was waiting for you.

355
00:42:35,388 --> 00:42:37,724
Any luck?

356
00:42:37,807 --> 00:42:39,893
I think we should check
those hallway closets.

357
00:42:39,976 --> 00:42:43,772
It's fine with me.
They are right here.
Thank you.

358
00:42:48,693 --> 00:42:51,279
There you are...
and there.

359
00:42:54,532 --> 00:42:56,451
Can we look in these bags?
Yes, fine.

360
00:43:14,010 --> 00:43:16,721
Why do you have things
in pairs, like twins?

361
00:43:16,805 --> 00:43:18,723
You have a twin.

362
00:43:18,807 --> 00:43:20,975
I have a television commercial
to do some time...

363
00:43:21,059 --> 00:43:24,479
and in case I should get
the makeup on the dress,

364
00:43:24,521 --> 00:43:26,815
then there is another one
for the next take.

365
00:43:26,898 --> 00:43:29,859
You see, uh,
I'm a model.

366
00:43:29,943 --> 00:43:31,861
And some time
an actress too.

367
00:43:31,945 --> 00:43:35,365
You certainly are.
That will do, Miss Collier.

368
00:43:35,448 --> 00:43:38,785
I'm sorry to have
troubled you, Miss Breton.

369
00:43:38,868 --> 00:43:42,414
I'm coming, I'm coming.
I'm sure you'll
report it to the police.

370
00:43:42,497 --> 00:43:44,874
Oh, yes.
By withholding evidence,

371
00:43:44,958 --> 00:43:47,460
you can make yourself
an accessory after the fact.

372
00:43:47,544 --> 00:43:50,422
 If I do hear anything,
I'll telephone you.

373
00:43:50,505 --> 00:43:53,633
Oh, excuse me.

374
00:43:55,385 --> 00:43:57,303
Oh!
Hello, darling. Am I late?

375
00:43:57,387 --> 00:43:59,723
No. Officer Kelly,
this is my, uh, husband...

376
00:43:59,806 --> 00:44:03,810
my ex-husband, Emil Breton,
and Officer Spinetti.

377
00:44:03,893 --> 00:44:07,522
 Now you have done something
naughty and the police have found out.

378
00:44:07,564 --> 00:44:11,359
 No, they tell me
that they look for a dead body.

379
00:44:11,401 --> 00:44:13,778
Are you serious?

380
00:44:13,862 --> 00:44:16,740
 Well, the lady claims
she saw a murder victim.

381
00:44:16,823 --> 00:44:21,494
Mind if I ask you a few questions?
No, not if I can help.

382
00:44:21,578 --> 00:44:23,788
Just what
is your full name?

383
00:44:23,872 --> 00:44:28,293
Emil Breton.
How long have you
and Mrs. Breton been divorced?

384
00:44:28,376 --> 00:44:31,838
We are not divorced.
We are separated.

385
00:44:31,921 --> 00:44:35,383
Dominique and Danielle!
She "does" have a twin! Oh!

386
00:44:45,018 --> 00:44:47,937
It was right...
right here.

387
00:45:00,575 --> 00:45:02,869
Listen...
Listen. One more word out of
you and I'm going to book you.

388
00:45:02,952 --> 00:45:06,039
I'll book you on something. I'll find
something in the book to book you on.

389
00:45:06,122 --> 00:45:08,083
Attempted libel,
assault on a police officer...

390
00:45:08,166 --> 00:45:10,043
I don't care what it is,
but I'll do it.

391
00:45:10,126 --> 00:45:12,253
I saw a murder,
and I'll prove it.

392
00:45:12,295 --> 00:45:15,215
Listen, Miss Collier, I don't know
what kind of a nut you are,

393
00:45:15,298 --> 00:45:17,509
or what kind of an exposé
you're looking to get,

394
00:45:17,592 --> 00:45:20,804
but just don't bother me
or that girl upstairs, okay?

395
00:45:20,887 --> 00:45:25,141
Far as I'm concerned, this case
is closed, you got that? Closed!

396
00:45:43,618 --> 00:45:48,039
Grace, I thought we were
supposed to meet upstairs.

397
00:45:48,123 --> 00:45:50,041
What are you
doing here?

398
00:45:50,125 --> 00:45:52,836
Grace, it's Tuesday.

399
00:45:52,919 --> 00:45:54,838
Oh, I forgot.

400
00:45:54,921 --> 00:45:56,923
Um, well, let's go.

401
00:45:57,007 --> 00:46:00,093
Honey, don't you think
you ought to change into
something a little bit more...

402
00:46:00,176 --> 00:46:02,303
Yeah, I'll change.
I'll meet you at the car, okay?

403
00:46:15,025 --> 00:46:17,402
Honey, I thought we were
going upstairs to have a little chat,

404
00:46:17,485 --> 00:46:19,404
and if you were embarrassed
about the mess,

405
00:46:19,487 --> 00:46:23,158
you know I'm always glad
to help you tidy up.

406
00:46:23,241 --> 00:46:27,245
Although, what you're going to do
when you get married, I don't know.

407
00:46:27,329 --> 00:46:30,999
Oh, did I tell you
the Cunningham girl is engaged?

408
00:46:31,041 --> 00:46:34,919
She's about your age, and she finally
found somebody that suits her.

409
00:46:35,003 --> 00:46:36,921
He's a doctor.

410
00:46:37,005 --> 00:46:40,425
Well, he's a veterinarian,
but the animals are all
owned by wealthy people...

411
00:46:40,508 --> 00:46:42,969
and he has
his own hospital.

412
00:46:43,053 --> 00:46:45,889
So you see, honey? Just because things
aren't working out...

413
00:46:45,972 --> 00:46:49,267
with you and your editor...
Uh, what's his name? ...Jim?

414
00:46:49,351 --> 00:46:51,811
I don't want to discuss that.
Oh.

415
00:46:51,895 --> 00:46:55,023
Well, I'm not trying
to interfere, honey.

416
00:46:55,065 --> 00:46:59,194
But you know, this doctor has
a very interesting young assistant.

417
00:46:59,235 --> 00:47:01,613
Grace, that reminds me.

418
00:47:01,696 --> 00:47:03,615
They've started
right in our neighborhood,

419
00:47:03,698 --> 00:47:05,867
and I don't know whether the zoning laws
are going to permit it.

420
00:47:05,909 --> 00:47:08,536
And I just don't know
how they got away with it.

421
00:47:08,620 --> 00:47:12,040
But three or four blocks away
from us... Are you listening, honey?

422
00:47:12,123 --> 00:47:15,877
Because this would make a very
interesting story for your newspaper.

423
00:47:15,960 --> 00:47:19,214
An experimental
madhouse.

424
00:47:19,255 --> 00:47:23,218
Now, you see, what's worse is that
they just let them walk around.

425
00:47:23,301 --> 00:47:26,680
The whole idea is that instead
of locking them up,

426
00:47:26,763 --> 00:47:28,890
they let them live
in a house...

427
00:47:28,932 --> 00:47:31,142
and the doctors make
a home for them,

428
00:47:31,226 --> 00:47:35,730
and it's sort of a family situation,
just like real people.

429
00:47:37,440 --> 00:47:41,069
It's very advanced.
I saw something about it on television.

430
00:47:41,152 --> 00:47:43,071
Now you see, honey?
There are interesting things...

431
00:47:43,154 --> 00:47:46,741
going on right here
on Staten Island.

432
00:47:46,783 --> 00:47:49,869
But I tell you,
I don't feel safe at night.

433
00:47:49,953 --> 00:47:51,871
Would you stop here? Pull over.
Why?

434
00:48:10,390 --> 00:48:12,308
Everything looks so...

435
00:48:12,392 --> 00:48:14,310
If you want pastry,
let's wait and get it at Brian's.

436
00:48:14,394 --> 00:48:16,312
I don't want
any pastry.

437
00:48:19,983 --> 00:48:22,569
Did a man come in here
this morning and buy a birthday cake?

438
00:48:22,652 --> 00:48:25,947
Lady, ten men came in
and bought ten birthday cakes.

439
00:48:25,989 --> 00:48:30,118
This cake had two names on it,
but written the way a child
writes, not the way a...

440
00:48:30,160 --> 00:48:34,080
Oh, yeah. The colored guy that
made me write on the cake.

441
00:48:34,164 --> 00:48:37,834
What were the names?
I don't know.

442
00:48:37,917 --> 00:48:40,003
Daisy and Debbie.

443
00:48:40,086 --> 00:48:42,005
Dominique and Danielle.

444
00:48:42,088 --> 00:48:44,174
That's what it was.
Yeah! That's it.

445
00:48:44,257 --> 00:48:46,509
I did it,
and I don't even remember.

446
00:48:46,593 --> 00:48:49,679
Can I have your names, please?
What for?

447
00:48:49,763 --> 00:48:53,266
My name is Grace Collier, and I write
for "The Staten Island Panorama."

448
00:48:53,350 --> 00:48:56,144
And I'm her mother,
Mrs. Payson Collier.

449
00:48:56,186 --> 00:48:58,021
My girlfriend and I
read your column.

450
00:48:58,104 --> 00:49:00,982
My name
is Elaine Deanna.

451
00:49:01,024 --> 00:49:02,984
Deanna.

452
00:49:03,026 --> 00:49:07,447
And the other girl is Louise Wilanski.
Wilanski.

453
00:49:07,530 --> 00:49:11,368
What do you want to know?
Thank you. That's fine.

454
00:49:11,451 --> 00:49:15,455
Huh.
How do you like that?

455
00:49:15,538 --> 00:49:19,167
She says she's gonna write an article,
and she doesn't ask us any questions.

456
00:49:19,209 --> 00:49:22,796
They're just terrible
about deadlines.

457
00:49:22,879 --> 00:49:24,464
Next, please?

458
00:49:26,633 --> 00:49:29,636
Really, Grace,
you were rather abrupt.

459
00:49:29,719 --> 00:49:31,971
I happen to be working
on an assignment.

460
00:49:32,055 --> 00:49:35,058
Well, don't you think you're taking this
little job of yours a bit seriously?

461
00:49:35,141 --> 00:49:38,019
You're 25 years old. You should be
thinking about something else.

462
00:49:38,103 --> 00:49:40,021
I'm not gonna marry anybody.

463
00:49:40,105 --> 00:49:44,067
And I wish you'd stop referring
to my work as "a little job."

464
00:49:44,150 --> 00:49:46,069
I like to call what I do
a profession,

465
00:49:46,152 --> 00:49:50,240
only working for "The Staten Island"
"Panorama" is a bit of a joke.

466
00:49:50,323 --> 00:49:52,492
Do you know what
my next assignment is?
No, I don't.

467
00:49:52,575 --> 00:49:55,161
I'm having lunch tomorrow
with an 80-year-old ex-con...

468
00:49:55,245 --> 00:50:00,041
who's just carved an entire replica
of the Danbury Penitentiary out of soap.

469
00:50:00,125 --> 00:50:03,253
Oh, that's interesting.
Oh, I want to write about...

470
00:50:03,336 --> 00:50:05,255
about the apathy
in the police force.

471
00:50:05,338 --> 00:50:08,717
About where the heroin goes
after a bust. About the...
Shh!

472
00:50:08,800 --> 00:50:12,137
You don't have to shout
like you're on the street.

473
00:50:12,220 --> 00:50:14,139
What's the matter with you?
I've never seen you like this.

474
00:50:14,222 --> 00:50:17,934
I'm on to something big.
Are you on diet pills again?

475
00:50:18,018 --> 00:50:20,895
I can see that you
have your mind on other things.

476
00:50:20,979 --> 00:50:23,398
Can we have another date?
We "do" have another date.

477
00:50:23,440 --> 00:50:25,775
You have supper with us on Friday.
Fine.

478
00:50:25,859 --> 00:50:27,777
I'll be there.

479
00:50:30,071 --> 00:50:31,990
Well, can I
drop you somewhere?

480
00:50:32,073 --> 00:50:34,951
No. It's okay.
I'll walk.

481
00:50:35,035 --> 00:50:36,953
Well, it's not the way
we planned it, but...

482
00:50:38,788 --> 00:50:40,790
A white woman kills
her black lover,

483
00:50:40,832 --> 00:50:43,835
and those racist cops
couldn't care less.

484
00:50:43,918 --> 00:50:46,963
I saw it happen,
and they won't investigate.

485
00:50:50,216 --> 00:50:52,135
Well, if you're not
interested,

486
00:50:52,218 --> 00:50:54,554
I'm sure I can find
someone else who'd print it.

487
00:50:54,637 --> 00:50:56,556
Lots of people would.

488
00:51:02,562 --> 00:51:04,814
Good. You're interested.

489
00:51:04,898 --> 00:51:08,985
I'll do my own investigation.
Why not?

490
00:51:09,069 --> 00:51:11,029
I know more
than those idiot police.

491
00:51:11,112 --> 00:51:14,949
I know karate...
A private detective. Waste of money.

492
00:51:15,033 --> 00:51:17,077
I...

493
00:51:17,160 --> 00:51:19,788
All right.
All right, what's his name?

494
00:51:20,747 --> 00:51:22,666
"Joseph Larch."

495
00:51:46,523 --> 00:51:50,235
Now, I think the best
thing for us to do...
This is what we do.

496
00:51:50,318 --> 00:51:53,279
You go up to your apartment, call
Danielle, and see if anybody's home.

497
00:51:53,363 --> 00:51:55,824
If someone answers, wave once.
If no one is there, wave twice.

498
00:51:55,865 --> 00:51:57,826
Well, you're going up there
if no one's there?
Sure.

499
00:51:57,867 --> 00:51:59,828
All I have to do is know
the situation in advance.

500
00:51:59,869 --> 00:52:01,830
I can play it either way.
Well, in that case, I can pretend...

501
00:52:01,871 --> 00:52:04,499
to be making an informal
telephone survey...
You just do hand signals.

502
00:52:04,541 --> 00:52:06,501
If there's no one
up there,

503
00:52:06,543 --> 00:52:08,503
I can charm the superintendent
into giving me a passkey.

504
00:52:08,545 --> 00:52:11,423
No, you've got to make
a wax impression.
No one does that.

505
00:52:11,506 --> 00:52:14,259
Go up to your apartment,
watch the front while I'm up there,

506
00:52:14,342 --> 00:52:16,261
and if you see someone coming,
telephone the apartment.

507
00:52:16,344 --> 00:52:18,263
One ring. One ring and hang up.
Well, what if...

508
00:52:18,346 --> 00:52:20,432
Does that answer your question?
Yeah.

509
00:52:20,515 --> 00:52:22,600
But suppose that...
Hey, have you ever been a detective?

510
00:52:22,684 --> 00:52:24,602
No.
Have you?

511
00:52:24,686 --> 00:52:27,272
No, but simple logic suggests
a way of doing things.

512
00:52:27,355 --> 00:52:31,568
I don't see that it can be
all that mysterious.
Grace, this is a craft.

513
00:52:31,651 --> 00:52:33,945
I wouldn't try to teach you how
to write magazine articles.

514
00:52:34,029 --> 00:52:35,947
Listen, I went to school
to learn this...

515
00:52:36,031 --> 00:52:38,450
The Brooklyn Institute
of Modern Investigation. Okay?

516
00:52:38,533 --> 00:52:40,910
Okay.
Okay.

517
00:52:40,994 --> 00:52:43,955
Now, you go on up to your apartment
and do what I told you. Go ahead.

518
00:52:45,373 --> 00:52:47,292
I'll be here.

519
00:53:38,635 --> 00:53:40,011
Larch?

520
00:53:53,983 --> 00:53:55,860
The boxes.

521
00:54:28,768 --> 00:54:32,605
What?
Meet me in the truck.

522
00:54:40,030 --> 00:54:41,322
My God.

523
00:54:54,627 --> 00:54:57,213
Get out of there, Larch.

524
00:56:12,122 --> 00:56:14,582
We got to get
out of here.

525
00:56:29,639 --> 00:56:31,599
What was that you were waving?
I don't know,

526
00:56:31,641 --> 00:56:34,310
but they had it hidden in the bedroom,
so it might be something important.

527
00:56:34,394 --> 00:56:36,312
Take a look in it
while I tell you...

528
00:56:36,396 --> 00:56:38,606
about the real evidence
I found in the living room.

529
00:56:38,690 --> 00:56:41,067
I got up there
without any trouble.

530
00:56:41,151 --> 00:56:44,029
I did the usual search...
nothing.

531
00:56:44,112 --> 00:56:47,782
I began to think that cop
was right about you until
I tried to move that couch.

532
00:56:47,824 --> 00:56:50,702
I couldn't. It was too heavy.
The couch.

533
00:56:50,785 --> 00:56:54,039
Yeah. He's in the couch.
What?

534
00:56:54,122 --> 00:56:56,958
The body.
What about the body?

535
00:56:57,000 --> 00:56:58,960
What I went up there
to look for, remember?

536
00:56:59,002 --> 00:57:00,962
The body
is in the couch!

537
00:57:01,004 --> 00:57:04,591
Terrific!
And the murderess is in here!

538
00:57:04,674 --> 00:57:07,886
What?
Do you know what you've found?

539
00:57:07,969 --> 00:57:11,639
A complete file
on the Blanchion Twins.

540
00:57:11,723 --> 00:57:13,641
Now what are you talking about?
Do you remember...

541
00:57:13,725 --> 00:57:17,354
about a year ago, "Life" magazine
ran a whole story on them.

542
00:57:17,437 --> 00:57:19,939
The only Siamese twins...
Look, I was up there, Grace,

543
00:57:20,023 --> 00:57:23,360
and I know what I know and saw,
and I didn't see no Siamese twins.

544
00:57:23,443 --> 00:57:26,780
I do know that you have to have
a dead body before you have a murder.

545
00:57:26,863 --> 00:57:28,823
I gotta get going.
We gotta catch this ferry.

546
00:57:28,865 --> 00:57:31,951
You mean that's all you're gonna do...
locate the body and then split?

547
00:57:32,035 --> 00:57:34,329
Yes, for Quebec.
Quebec?

548
00:57:34,371 --> 00:57:36,331
That's where Breton
told them to take it.

549
00:57:36,373 --> 00:57:39,334
Now, wherever that couch goes,
I follow, because somebody's
gonna be waiting for it...

550
00:57:39,376 --> 00:57:41,336
at the other end,
and I want to know who.

551
00:57:41,378 --> 00:57:45,757
That makes sense.
Hey, lend me a dollar, will ya?

552
00:57:45,840 --> 00:57:48,468
When we get to Manhattan,
I'm gonna go see this writer,

553
00:57:48,510 --> 00:57:50,470
and then...
Then you go back to your apartment,

554
00:57:50,512 --> 00:57:52,972
lock the door, and wait
for me to call. Period.

555
00:58:18,415 --> 00:58:20,375
Where's Arthur McLennen's
office?

556
00:58:20,417 --> 00:58:22,377
Uh, end of the hall,
to your right.

557
00:58:33,680 --> 00:58:36,224
Uh, Miss, uh, Miss Collier?
Yes.

558
00:58:36,307 --> 00:58:38,727
Ah, yes.
Well, I'm, uh, I'm Arthur McLennen.

559
00:58:38,810 --> 00:58:40,729
How do you do?
Hello.

560
00:58:40,812 --> 00:58:44,733
I, uh, I'm afraid
I'm a little disorganized today.

561
00:58:44,816 --> 00:58:48,236
Are, uh, are you here
about, uh...

562
00:58:50,030 --> 00:58:54,326
Well. That's the Blanchion Twins file.
Yes, it is.

563
00:58:54,409 --> 00:58:56,494
Now, I know you did the story
over a year ago,

564
00:58:56,578 --> 00:58:59,205
but I was hoping you might remember
enough about it to help me.

565
00:58:59,289 --> 00:59:01,207
Oh, those poor girls.

566
00:59:02,792 --> 00:59:06,296
You know, this looks like the file
I saw at the Loisel Institute.

567
00:59:06,379 --> 00:59:08,840
Oh, it "is" the original, isn't it?
Yes, I believe it is.

568
00:59:08,923 --> 00:59:12,010
How'd you get it?
Are you going to do a follow-up?

569
00:59:12,093 --> 00:59:15,055
We never did. The managing editor
would never assign it.

570
00:59:15,138 --> 00:59:17,140
Well, they've asked me to find out
as much as I can about it.

571
00:59:17,223 --> 00:59:20,310
We're not quite sure
what kind of a piece we'd do.

572
00:59:20,393 --> 00:59:23,396
Oh, well, come on in
and we'll talk about it, huh?

573
00:59:24,647 --> 00:59:27,567
The subject
is a curious one.

574
00:59:27,609 --> 00:59:30,612
After we ran this story,
we got about 500 letters.

575
00:59:30,653 --> 00:59:35,784
No matter what else they said,
they all had that same tone
of morbid fascination.

576
00:59:35,825 --> 00:59:38,745
I don't excuse myself,
either.

577
00:59:38,828 --> 00:59:43,041
Though I actually met the Blanchion
girls, I was the same way.

578
00:59:43,124 --> 00:59:46,127
Hey. You know,
if you're going to do that piece,

579
00:59:46,211 --> 00:59:48,129
I've got something
I'd like to show you.

580
00:59:48,213 --> 00:59:51,424
Oh, I'd appreciate anything that...
You do have some time now?

581
00:59:51,466 --> 00:59:54,969
Of course!
Sometimes I forget myself
when I get going on a subject,

582
00:59:55,053 --> 00:59:57,972
but actually, if you have the time,
I'd like to show you a videotape.

583
00:59:58,014 --> 01:00:01,643
The more I learned,
the more interested I became.

584
01:00:01,726 --> 01:00:05,772
You see, to me at any rate,
the psychological and
philosophical elements...

585
01:00:05,814 --> 01:00:08,441
are of extreme importance.

586
01:00:08,483 --> 01:00:10,443
Yes. Fine.

587
01:00:11,695 --> 01:00:13,655
Well, there.
About to begin.

588
01:00:20,578 --> 01:00:24,457
 Conjoined twins,
called Siamese,

589
01:00:24,499 --> 01:00:28,128
challenge life
at their first breath.

590
01:00:28,211 --> 01:00:31,464
History had them
as the stuff of myth and symbol.

591
01:00:31,506 --> 01:00:35,635
Some tried to achieve
such normality as they could.

592
01:00:35,677 --> 01:00:39,681
The famous Chang and Eng,
the twins of Siamese birth...

593
01:00:39,764 --> 01:00:42,684
who gave this congenital
abnormality its popular name,

594
01:00:42,726 --> 01:00:46,855
married and fathered families.

595
01:00:46,938 --> 01:00:50,775
Other twins lived by hiring
themselves out to sideshows...

596
01:00:50,859 --> 01:00:53,987
or running
small town souvenir shops.

597
01:00:54,070 --> 01:00:58,658
With the sophisticated surgical
techniques developed in this century,

598
01:00:58,700 --> 01:01:02,746
some twins have been separated
and lead normal lives.

599
01:01:02,829 --> 01:01:06,833
Others never can.

600
01:01:06,916 --> 01:01:11,338
Born on March 27, 1948,
in Quebec, the Blanchions...

601
01:01:11,421 --> 01:01:13,882
were Canada's
first Siamese twins.

602
01:01:13,923 --> 01:01:19,346
Their parents died in an
automobile accident only days
before their first birthday.

603
01:01:19,429 --> 01:01:23,266
Dominique and Danielle
were to grow up...

604
01:01:23,350 --> 01:01:27,270
from then on within the pale walls
of the Loisel Institute,

605
01:01:27,354 --> 01:01:31,691
where surgeons, reluctant
to risk an operation on their
delicate spinal conjoinment,

606
01:01:31,733 --> 01:01:34,444
decided to let
them live as one.

607
01:01:34,527 --> 01:01:38,073
But whether as twins through life...
That's Danielle's husband.

608
01:01:38,156 --> 01:01:41,034
Who told you that?
I want to hear this.

609
01:01:41,117 --> 01:01:43,453
 There is always
a price to pay.

610
01:01:43,536 --> 01:01:47,040
It seems the older
they become,

611
01:01:47,123 --> 01:01:51,920
the more precarious
is their psychological balance,

612
01:01:51,961 --> 01:01:56,591
both within themselves
and between one another.

613
01:01:56,675 --> 01:01:59,886
In this, I am in agreement
with my colleagues.

614
01:01:59,928 --> 01:02:03,181
Although, they tend
to think that Dominique...

615
01:02:03,264 --> 01:02:06,726
is the truly disturbed one,

616
01:02:06,768 --> 01:02:11,314
I think they will find that
Danielle, who is so sweet,

617
01:02:11,398 --> 01:02:15,652
so responsive, so normal,

618
01:02:15,735 --> 01:02:18,113
as opposed to her sister,

619
01:02:18,196 --> 01:02:21,658
can only be so
because of her sister.

620
01:02:21,741 --> 01:02:25,078
Bonjour, Dominique.

621
01:02:25,161 --> 01:02:29,582
 This was the last interview
the conjoined twins would ever give.

622
01:02:29,666 --> 01:02:31,960
That night, the doctors
were forced by nature...

623
01:02:32,043 --> 01:02:35,296
to perform an operation
they had hoped to avoid.

624
01:02:35,338 --> 01:02:39,676
Late the next day, the institute
announced the successful separation.

625
01:02:39,759 --> 01:02:42,137
Dominique and Danielle,

626
01:02:42,220 --> 01:02:47,017
once one, would now
stand each alone.

627
01:02:47,100 --> 01:02:52,689
Well, what do you think?
That's an extraordinary
tape, Mr. McLennen.

628
01:02:52,772 --> 01:02:54,983
Now, I tried
to do a follow-up,

629
01:02:55,025 --> 01:02:58,361
but the institute was closed to me
even as a friend of the twins.

630
01:02:58,445 --> 01:03:01,948
Why was that?
Well, all I could find out
at the time was that...

631
01:03:01,990 --> 01:03:04,743
after the operation there
had been some complications.

632
01:03:04,826 --> 01:03:08,872
What sort of complications?
I never did get
any official information,

633
01:03:08,955 --> 01:03:12,375
so I slipped 20 bucks to one of the
suture nurses, and she told me that...

634
01:03:12,459 --> 01:03:15,337
Dominique Blanchion had died
on the operating table. 

635
01:08:29,526 --> 01:08:33,113
What are you doing?
I have my work to do.

636
01:08:36,282 --> 01:08:39,619
Do you live here?
So they tell me.

637
01:08:39,661 --> 01:08:43,581
Do you mind
if I use your telephone?

638
01:08:43,665 --> 01:08:46,084
No.
Where is it?

639
01:08:46,167 --> 01:08:48,628
It's in the kitchen
down the hall.

640
01:08:48,670 --> 01:08:50,672
Thank you.

641
01:09:08,982 --> 01:09:13,987
Better spray yourself, hon.
You're not supposed to be in here.

642
01:09:14,070 --> 01:09:16,823
I've got
to use the telephone.

643
01:09:16,865 --> 01:09:21,161
You're not supposed
to be in here.

644
01:09:21,202 --> 01:09:23,204
I think you have a cold.

645
01:09:24,873 --> 01:09:28,293
No, no.

646
01:09:31,129 --> 01:09:34,090
It's a clean telephone.

647
01:09:37,218 --> 01:09:41,264
Don't just think you can
walk in here like that.

648
01:09:43,808 --> 01:09:48,271
Did you know that the germs
can come through the wires?

649
01:09:48,355 --> 01:09:52,942
I never call
and I never answer.

650
01:09:53,026 --> 01:09:56,321
It's a good way
to get sick.

651
01:09:56,404 --> 01:09:59,949
Very, very sick.

652
01:10:00,033 --> 01:10:04,454
That's how I got so sick.
Someone called me on the telephone!

653
01:10:04,537 --> 01:10:07,832
What's going on here?
Who are you?

654
01:10:07,916 --> 01:10:11,169
My name is Grace Collier and I write
for "The Staten Island Panorama,"

655
01:10:11,252 --> 01:10:14,255
and I must use the telephone.
No!

656
01:10:14,339 --> 01:10:17,217
 No!
Don't give it to her. Don't!

657
01:10:17,258 --> 01:10:19,886
She won't use it, Arlene.
She won't.

658
01:10:19,969 --> 01:10:22,472
Trust me.

659
01:10:25,809 --> 01:10:30,271
Look, this is the Lynton Clinic.
You can't just come
walking in here like this.

660
01:10:30,313 --> 01:10:33,400
Well I can if one of your patients is
roaming around loose murdering people.

661
01:10:33,483 --> 01:10:37,278
Oh, come on. There have been a lot of
wild rumors going around about us,

662
01:10:37,320 --> 01:10:39,531
but I wouldn't expect the "Panorama"
to take them seriously.

663
01:10:39,614 --> 01:10:42,283
I take them seriously
and I'm going to call the police!

664
01:10:42,325 --> 01:10:44,786
Better talk to the head of the clinic.
Now, if you call about 10:00 tomorrow...

665
01:10:44,828 --> 01:10:47,288
I'll speak
to him now!

666
01:10:47,330 --> 01:10:51,126
I'll see if he'll see you.
He's probably gone to bed.

667
01:10:52,419 --> 01:10:54,796
Hello, Doctor.
I'm sorry to disturb you.

668
01:10:54,838 --> 01:10:58,341
There's a girl here who says she's
"a reporter from the" Panorama.

669
01:10:58,425 --> 01:11:01,302
She insists
on talking to you.

670
01:11:01,386 --> 01:11:03,513
Okay.

671
01:11:05,306 --> 01:11:07,642
Doctor will be
right with you. Arlene...

672
01:11:07,726 --> 01:11:12,772
You did a good job cleaning up.

673
01:11:12,856 --> 01:11:17,152
Now, you can take your things
back to the supply room.

674
01:11:35,962 --> 01:11:39,674
One of your patients is a murderess.

675
01:11:39,716 --> 01:11:43,678
I followed her here tonight. Now, we've
got to call the police. That's him!

676
01:11:43,720 --> 01:11:46,348
Dr. Breton, this girl says
she's from the "Panorama."

677
01:11:46,431 --> 01:11:49,476
Hello, Margaret,
why aren't you in your room?

678
01:11:49,517 --> 01:11:52,771
This man is involved in a murder
and we have got to call the police.

679
01:11:52,854 --> 01:11:56,399
She came to us last night. We're
very happy to have her join our family.

680
01:11:56,483 --> 01:11:58,818
Oh, I was off duty.

681
01:11:58,860 --> 01:12:02,864
Margaret, this is Mr. Jansen.
Margaret Grisham.

682
01:12:02,947 --> 01:12:06,284
Hello, Margaret.
Nice try.

683
01:12:06,368 --> 01:12:08,578
If you'll go and check my I.D.,
it's in my car outside.

684
01:12:08,662 --> 01:12:10,538
I am Grace Collier.

685
01:12:10,622 --> 01:12:16,336
I wouldn't insist on "Margaret" right
away. We want to respect your wishes.

686
01:12:16,378 --> 01:12:19,506
When you're ready to have us
call you Margaret, you tell us.

687
01:12:19,547 --> 01:12:22,926
Take her to room 23.
Right.

688
01:12:23,009 --> 01:12:25,929
Dr. Corbin, prepare her
for hypnotherapy.

689
01:12:28,723 --> 01:12:32,936
Come with me, Margaret.
Grace, I mean. It's all right.

690
01:12:39,567 --> 01:12:42,237
Please. Now, you've
got to believe me.

691
01:12:42,320 --> 01:12:46,491
I am perfectly sane. Just go downstairs
and check my bag. It's in my car.

692
01:12:46,574 --> 01:12:49,035
Yes, Grace. Just as soon
as you're settled in.
No! Now!

693
01:12:49,077 --> 01:12:52,122
I'm afraid my life is in danger.
I understand.

694
01:12:52,205 --> 01:12:54,207
Oh, God!
I know what that sounds like.

695
01:12:54,249 --> 01:12:57,252
I'm serious. As soon
as you find out who I am,

696
01:12:57,335 --> 01:12:59,337
you'll know that they are
making all of this up!

697
01:12:59,421 --> 01:13:01,798
Grace, I believe
you're serious in what you think.

